      Don=E2=80=99t forget to vote
   =20
 =20
Churchill Capital Corp. IV is a special purpose acquisition company, a pot =
of money worth about $10.00 for each share that it issued. Its stock closed=
 yesterday at $22.90 per share, which is more than $10.00. This is because =
it has announced a plan to merge with Lucid Motors Inc., an electric-vehicl=
e company, and Churchill shareholders are excited about this merger and thi=
nk it is a good deal.[1] If Churchill closes its deal with Lucid, Churchill=
 shareholders will have Lucid stock that they think is worth $22.90. If it =
does not close its deal with Lucid, they=E2=80=99ll get their $10 back in c=
ash. They would prefer the $22.90.[2]They would prefer the $22.90, but they=
 would not=C2=A0necessarily prefer it enough  to do anything about it:The b=
lank-check company seeking to buy electric-car startup Lucid Motors Inc. ma=
de a last-minute appeal for retail shareholders to vote for the deal amid s=
igns that it=E2=80=99s struggling to win their approval.Churchill Capital C=
orp. IV, the special purpose acquisition company started by investment bank=
er Michael Klein, adjourned its Thursday shareholder meeting that was to de=
termine the fate of the merger, pushing the decision back to the following =
day. It also appealed again in a new statement for shareholders to sign off=
 on the deal. Churchill=E2=80=99s shares fell as much as 4.8% before retrac=
ing about half the loss.=E2=80=9CThe company still needs additional votes t=
o obtain approval for that proposal by a majority of its outstanding shares=
,=E2=80=9D according to the statement. =E2=80=9CAs a result, the meeting ha=
s been adjourned to obtain the required votes.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CW=
e welcome all of the new shareholders,=E2=80=9D Klein said. =E2=80=9CHoweve=
r, we need you to participate in the election process. In particular, if yo=
u are participating from the new trading platforms, the new apps that may n=
ot necessarily be directing you clearly to a voting service, we need your v=
ote,=E2=80=9D Klein said. He added that the process =E2=80=9Cliterally take=
s one minute.=E2=80=9DMultiple notices have been sent to shareholders, with=
 Lucid Chief Executive Officer Peter Rawlinson singling out Robinhood users=
 =E2=80=9Cwith those diamond hands=E2=80=9D in a video posted to social med=
ia earlier this week. The voting deadline was extended Thursday morning jus=
t hours before the meeting was set to take place. Churchill also asked inve=
stors who were holders of record to vote even if they=E2=80=99ve already so=
ld their shares.It worked out fine; they approved the merger this morning. =
Virtually everyone who voted =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Capproximately 98% of v=
otes cast=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0voted yes.[3] But they needed a majority =
of Churchill=E2=80=99s total shares outstanding to vote yes, and it was a s=
truggle just to get enough people to vote.[4] And this is for an=C2=A0obvio=
usly good deal, one where the stock was trading much higher ($22.90) than t=
he cash value ($10) of the SPAC. There was a ton of enthusiasm for this mer=
ger and it still struggled to get approved. For deals with less enthusiasm =
that could be a problem.The problem was some combination of:=09Lots of SPAC=
 investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly in hot electric-vehicle SPAC deals l=
ike Churchill/Lucid =E2=80=94=C2=A0are retail shareholders who have never b=
othered to vote their shares, either because they are inexperienced and new=
 to investing or just because there is almost no context where a retail sha=
reholder=E2=80=99s vote could possibly matter. Voting on nonbinding say-on-=
pay proposals, or even mergers, rarely matters because most companies=E2=80=
=99 shareholder bases are dominated by institutions with lots of shares, so=
 you figure the institutions will decide the question and it=E2=80=99s not =
worth voting your 10 shares. Here, there are fewer institutions,[5] so your=
 shares are worth voting.=09Relatedly, if you bought your shares on Robinho=
od, Robinhood is not exactly laser-focused on getting you to vote. (=E2=80=
=9COne person involved in the Lucid deal said: =E2=80=98Robinhood needs to =
focus on this. It=E2=80=99s not right for their users.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D)=
=09The stock trades like 10 million shares a day. (There are 207 million sh=
ares outstanding.) The record date for the vote was June 21. If you owned s=
tock on June 21, you get to vote. If you bought stock after June 21, you do=
n=E2=80=99t. If you owned stock on June 21 and then sold it, you still get =
to vote. But you are unlikely to care very much. =E2=80=9CStockholders as o=
f the close of business on June 21, 2021, the record date for the Special M=
eeting, should vote their shares even if they no longer own them,=E2=80=9D =
said Churchill in  its press release yesterday, but why should they? It doe=
sn=E2=80=99t affect them anymore. They sold their stock; if the merger fail=
s, they keep their money, and can have a good laugh at the people who bough=
t the stock from them.=C2=A0To the extent SPACs are owned by rapidly day-tr=
ading retail shareholders, this is going to be a continuing problem. The go=
od news is that the retail day traders seem to be particularly concentrated=
 in the hottest SPACs, which have the highest prices, so their holders have=
 the most incentive to actually vote. A SPAC that announces a deal and trad=
es to $10.15 is not going to get all that much enthusiasm, but nor is it go=
ing to attract hordes of Robinhood traders who just forget to vote. Churchi=
ll did attract those hordes, and they did forget to vote, but eventually it=
 was able to track them down and point out that it was in their best intere=
sts to vote.
