      Private markets are the new public markets
   =20
 =20
In the U.S., the principal=C2=A0legal=C2=A0difference between a =E2=80=9Cpu=
blic=E2=80=9D company and a =E2=80=9Cprivate=E2=80=9D company is that you h=
ave to be rich to buy shares of a private company, while anyone can buy sha=
res of a public company. Public companies=E2=80=99 stocks trade on the stoc=
k exchange, and anyone can open a brokerage account and buy stocks. Private=
 companies=E2=80=99 stocks trade in private transactions, which are subject=
 to more complicated rules, but generally speaking if you are an =E2=80=9Ca=
ccredited investor=E2=80=9D you are allowed to buy them.[6] The way to qual=
ify as an accredited investor is, traditionally, to have enough money: a ne=
t worth (excluding primary residence) of at least $1 million, or income of =
at least $200,000 per year (or $300,000 for a couple). Recent amendments to=
 the accredited-investor rules allow you to be accredited by knowledge (bas=
ically having a securities license) rather than money. And of course basica=
lly any=C2=A0institutional investor will be=C2=A0=E2=80=9Caccredited.=E2=80=
=9DSo the rough traditional rule is that anyone can buy public stocks, but =
only institutional investors, hedge funds, dentists, doctors, lawyers, prof=
essional athletes, small-business owners =E2=80=A6=C2=A0honestly it is quit=
e a long list of people who can buy private stocks? =E2=80=9CAccredited inv=
estor=E2=80=9D used to be a pretty exclusive category, but it is much less =
exclusive today. =E2=80=9CWhen the SEC first set its rules of entry for pri=
vate markets in 1982, only 1.5 million households made the cut=E2=80=9D; by=
 2018, even=C2=A0before the recent amendments to expand the definition,=C2=
=A0that number was =E2=80=9Cmore than 16 million U.S. households=E2=80=94ab=
out one in eight.=E2=80=9DBut this legal difference dramatically understate=
s the practical difference between public and private companies.=C2=A0If yo=
u are a prosperous dentist, you are allowed to buy shares in private compan=
ies, but most private companies won=E2=80=99t sell you any shares. When pri=
vate companies want to raise money, they go to big investors =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0venture capitalists and private equity funds but also mutual funds and h=
edge funds and strategic investors and SoftBank=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and rai=
se large chunks of money. And they typically restrict those investors from =
reselling their stock, so a market doesn=E2=80=99t really develop. And wher=
eas public stocks trade on the stock exchange and you can see the price and=
 put in an order to buy, private stocks, even when they do trade, usually d=
on=E2=80=99t trade on an organized exchange and you can=E2=80=99t just buy =
them through your broker. You have to know the person who=E2=80=99s selling=
 them, if you want to buy them. And if you want to sell them, you have to k=
now someone who=E2=80=99s looking to buy.One result of this is that, if you=
 are a prosperous dentist, you can buy the same stock in the same public co=
mpanies on the same terms as the fanciest hedge fund, but your universe of=
=C2=A0private=C2=A0investment opportunities will be totally different from =
the options available to brand-name venture capitalists and SoftBank. You w=
ill never see any of the deals they see, and they will never see any of the=
 deals you see. Probably the deals you see will be worse! Because they have=
 lots of money and sophistication, and you have just enough money and sophi=
stication to be accredited.If you run a company, you might want to be publi=
c. There are various advantages to that; the main one is that=C2=A0you can =
raise money from absolutely anyone. Not so long ago, I was fond of downplay=
ing this advantage: Private markets were absolutely awash in money, it was =
easy to raise billions of dollars from large institutional investors, and t=
he main advantage of public markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they were where all=
 the money was =E2=80=94=C2=A0was diminished. The meme-stock rally has chan=
ged my perspective. Now public companies can raise hundreds of millions of =
dollars in a few hours at enormous valuations in at-the-market offerings to=
 wildly enthusiastic retail investors, which you can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0do if y=
ou=E2=80=99re private. That does seem like a big advantage to being public?=
Still,=C2=A0you might instead want to be private. There are various advanta=
ges to that. One is that you don=E2=80=99t have to file lots of disclosure =
documents (with risk factors, descriptions of your business, audited financ=
ial statements, etc.) with the Securities and Exchange Commission. You save=
 money on lawyers, you get to be a bit more secretive, you get sued less, e=
tc. Another advantage is that you get to control your shareholder base. You=
 can sell stock to investors you choose, and you can restrict their ability=
 to resell it. If you don=E2=80=99t want activists or corporate raiders or =
short-term-focused Wall Streeters or competitors or whoever to buy your sto=
ck, you don=E2=80=99t let them. You can=E2=80=99t generally do that as a pu=
blic company.But is there a compromise? Like what about this?=09You are leg=
ally not a public company and don=E2=80=99t have to comply with the SEC=E2=
=80=99s disclosure rules; but=09You can sell stock to as many people as pos=
sible, and those people can=C2=A0resell=C2=A0their stock to as many people =
as possible, on some sort of centralized exchange that can match up buyers =
and sellers efficiently rather than by word of mouth; but=09If there are pa=
rticular people who you don=E2=80=99t want buying your stock, you can ban t=
hem.You could imagine a category like =E2=80=9Cas public as possible withou=
t actually=C2=A0being public.=E2=80=9D Your stock trades electronically on =
a centralized exchange, there are market makers and quoted prices, and anyo=
ne who wants to buy it can buy it=C2=A0as long as they are accredited,[7] w=
hich is a minority of Americans but now a fairly large minority. (And an ev=
en larger minority of=C2=A0people who buy stocks.) If you want to raise mon=
ey, you can try to sell stock to all the dentists who trade on the exchange=
, though realistically the more appealing option is probably to sell stock =
to big institutions but promise them liquidity in the form of being able to=
=C2=A0resell=C2=A0their stock to the dentists whenever they want.=C2=A0The =
appeal for companies=C2=A0is the broadest possible access to capital withou=
t being public: You can sell to venture funds and hedge funds and mutual fu=
nds and everyone else who invests privately, but also dentists. The appeal =
for institutional investors is: You can buy stock in private companies and =
resell it, to dentists or to other institutions, in a fairly liquid and tra=
nsparent market. The appeal for dentists is: You can buy stock in private c=
ompanies that have institutional investors, instead of private companies th=
at only pitch their stock to dentists.There are also obvious benefits for i=
ntermediaries. The appeal for the private-company exchange=C2=A0is of cours=
e that you can charge higher fees to investors than a public exchange would=
. The appeal for brokers =E2=80=94=C2=A0the investment banks and broker-dea=
lers=C2=A0who would ordinarily be matching buyers and sellers of private-co=
mpany stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that their job is a lot less labor-intensive=
 if people are just putting in orders to buy or sell private stock on an ex=
change.Anyway:In the past year, a spate of companies have launched private =
trading platforms to keep up with market demand for access to assets that a=
re not publicly traded, including those that haven=E2=80=99t yet been tappe=
d by a private equity or venture firm.Most recently, Nasdaq, SVB Financial,=
 Citi, Goldman Sachs, and Morgan Stanley on Tuesday announced a joint ventu=
re to build a secondary trading platform for institutional investors. =C2=
=A0=C2=A0The platform will allow investors to access and execute private co=
mpany stock transactions using technology. According to the announcement, t=
his will increase transparency for investors. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe one thing =
that I think we can all agree to at this point is that the secondary market=
s are not a moment in time need,=E2=80=9D Eric Folkemer, president of Nasda=
q Private Market, told Institutional Investor. =E2=80=9CMany of the stakeho=
lders or employees expect it to a degree, especially as companies are stayi=
ng private longer.=E2=80=9D ...Nasdaq Private Market isn=E2=80=99t the only=
 firm entering the industry, though. CartaX, for instance, launched its bus=
iness earlier this year, pitching liquidity for private company shareholder=
s and access to these assets for institutional investors.=C2=A0Meanwhile, I=
nvestX, a private equity marketplace for broker-dealers that has been opera=
ting since 2014, launched GEM, its trading platform, in February. =C2=A0=E2=
=80=9CI did a lot of research on private markets, and I saw a growing marke=
t, one that was pistol hot,=E2=80=9D said Brian Schaeffer, managing directo=
r at the firm, by phone. =E2=80=9CDemand was so great that you could see th=
at the SEC would have to pay attention.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CThe SEC =
is going to look at this and look at it very hard,=E2=80=9D Schaeffer said.=
 For one, he added, the regulatory body is looking to redefine what an accr=
edited investor should look like, which could change the clientele of these=
 platforms. =C2=A0The pitches here seem to be mostly about liquidity for em=
ployees and trading opportunities for institutions; nobody has quite come o=
ut with a =E2=80=9Cbe as public as possible without being public=E2=80=9D p=
itch to companies, or for that matter made a big push to sign up every dent=
ist in America to their private-company exchange.To be fair, my tag line he=
re =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cprivate markets are the new public markets=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0was=C2=A0more=C2=A0true a few years ago; public markets =
have had a bit of a resurgence recently as a lot of the big crop of recent =
unicorns have gone public, SoftBank=E2=80=99s money has lost some of its al=
lure, and the meme-stock craze has made companies appreciate the benefits o=
f being public. It is not clear that many companies would actually want thi=
s combination of being technically private while having maximum access to i=
nvestors, or that many dentists would actually want to sign up for this pla=
tform instead of just trading public stocks on Robinhood. Still I kind of w=
ant someone to try.


