loomberg=E2=80=99s HDS list, of shareholders big or institutional enough to=
 disclose their holdings, covers 13.17% of the shares outstanding. At Apple=
 Inc. that number is 60.84%. At Tesla Inc. it is 65.22%. At JPMorgan Chase =
& Co. it=E2=80=99s 75.82%.[6] To be clear, the rules are more complicated, =
and people who are not accredited investors=C2=A0can definitely buy private=
 stocks in various contexts. But there are limits on that, whereas basicall=
y anyone who=E2=80=99s accredited=C2=A0can buy private stocks.=C2=A0[7] Or:=
 Anyone who is accredited and wants to buy it can buy it, except for a list=
 of excluded names that you provide to the exchange. If you=E2=80=99re not =
a public company, there=E2=80=99s no rule that everyone has to have equal a=
ccess.[8] Or=C2=A0a percentage of the CEO=E2=80=99s own compensation, like =
a talent agent.[9] This post from Alex Danco contrasting the Silicon Valley=
 and Canadian tech scenes informs my thinking on this point. He writes: =E2=
=80=9CGood Angels are playing an infinite game. They are contributing to a =
community; not in order to win something definite, but to earn the right to=
 keep participating in the scene. They play the infinite game of growing th=
eir status within a growing community, which is a very good thing. And they=
 often make a ton of money, leading to the perplexing advice for outsiders:=
 =E2=80=98the way to make money angel investing is to not set out trying to=
 make money.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D[10] That is, a bit after 10 a.m. today, I se=
e the $60 strike 20-Aug-21 call last traded at $1.99 on Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=
 OMON screen, with the stock in the high $35s. Options generally trade in c=
ontracts on 100 shares.[11] I mean, you=E2=80=99ll pay $6,000 to exercise t=
he option on 100 shares and sell them for $7,200, making $1,200, or $1,000 =
after deducting your $200 premium.
