om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Don=E2=80=99t forget to vote</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Churchill Capital Corp. IV is a specia=
l purpose acquisition company, a pot of money <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4MTEyMTAvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDg1Mzg0L3RtMjE5MzU5LTEyXz=
QyNGIzLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41df8de0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" title=3D"see page 15 on redemption rights" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">worth about $10.00</a> for each share that it issued. Its stock close=
d yesterday at $22.90 per share, which is more than $10.00. This is because=
 it has announced a plan to merge with Lucid Motors Inc., an electric-vehic=
le company, and Churchill shareholders are excited about this merger and th=
ink it is a good deal.[1] If Churchill closes its deal with Lucid, Churchil=
l shareholders will have Lucid stock that they think is worth $22.90. If it=
 does not close its deal with Lucid, they=E2=80=99ll get their $10 back in =
cash. They would prefer the $22.90.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They=
 would prefer the $22.90, but they would not=C2=A0<em>necessarily </em>pref=
er it enough <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537=
013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDct=
MjIvZXYtc3RhcnR1cC1sdWNpZC1yaXNrcy1jb2xsYXBzZS1vZi1zcGFjLWRlYWwtb24tbm8tc2h=
vdy1ob2xkZXJz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB479c7952" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> to do anything about it</a>:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The blank-check company seeking to bu=
y electric-car startup Lucid Motors Inc. made a last-minute appeal for reta=
il shareholders to vote for the deal amid signs that it=E2=80=99s strugglin=
g to win their approval.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Churchill Capital =
Corp. IV, the special purpose acquisition company started by investment ban=
ker Michael Klein, adjourned its Thursday shareholder meeting that was to d=
etermine the fate of the merger, pushing the decision back to the following=
 day. It also appealed again in a new statement for shareholders to sign of=
f on the deal. Churchill=E2=80=99s shares fell as much as 4.8% before retra=
cing about half the loss.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe comp=
any still needs additional votes to obtain approval for that proposal by a =
majority of its outstanding shares,=E2=80=9D according to the statement. =
=E2=80=9CAs a result, the meeting has been adjourned to obtain the required=
 votes.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe welc=
ome all of the new shareholders,=E2=80=9D Klein said. =E2=80=9CHowever, we =
need you to participate in the election process. In particular, if you are =
participating from the new trading platforms, the new apps that may not nec=
essarily be directing you clearly to a voting service, we need your vote,=
=E2=80=9D Klein said. He added that the process =E2=80=9Cliterally takes on=
e minute.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Multiple notices have be=
en sent to shareholders, with Lucid Chief Executive Officer Peter Rawlinson=
 singling out Robinhood users =E2=80=9Cwith those diamond hands=E2=80=9D in=
 a video posted to social media earlier this week. The voting deadline was =
extended Thursday morning just hours before the meeting was set to take pla=
ce. Churchill also asked investors who were holders of record to vote even =
if they=E2=80=99ve already sold their shares.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">It worked out fine; they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJuZXdzd2lyZS5jb20v=
bmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy9jaHVyY2hpbGwtY2FwaXRhbC1jb3JwLWl2LXN0b2NraG9sZGVycy1hcHB=
yb3ZlLWx1Y2lkLWJ1c2luZXNzLWNvbWJpbmF0aW9uLTMwMTM0MDIxNy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBc878e66f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">approved the merger</a> this morning. Virtually everyone who v=
oted =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Capproximately 98% of votes cast=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0voted yes.[3] But they needed a majority of Churchill=E2=80=99s=
 total shares outstanding to vote yes, and it was a struggle just to get en=
ough people to vote.[4] And this is for an=C2=A0<em>obviously good deal</em=
>, one where the stock was trading much higher ($22.90) than the cash value=
 ($10) of the SPAC. There was a ton of enthusiasm for this merger and it st=
ill struggled to get approved. For deals with less enthusiasm that could be=
 a problem.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem was some combinatio=
n of:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin:=
 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Lots of SPAC investors =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0particularly in hot electric-vehicle SPAC deals like Churchill/=
Lucid =E2=80=94=C2=A0are retail shareholders who have never bothered to vot=
e their shares, either because they are inexperienced and new to investing =
or just because there is almost no context where a retail shareholder=E2=80=
=99s vote could possibly matter. Voting on nonbinding say-on-pay proposals,=
 or even mergers, rarely matters because most companies=E2=80=99 shareholde=
r bases are dominated by institutions with lots of shares, so you figure th=
e institutions will decide the question and it=E2=80=99s not worth voting y=
our 10 shares. Here, there are fewer institutions,[5] so your shares are wo=
rth voting.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Relatedly, if you boug=
ht your shares on Robinhood, Robinhood is not exactly laser-focused on gett=
ing you to vote. (=E2=80=9COne person <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMTA=
yYjJiOTQtZjY0YS00MmY1LTkzZWUtNDU4NDFkNTRmNTc2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9a43=
c334" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">invo=
lved in the Lucid deal said</a>: =E2=80=98Robinhood needs to focus on this.=
 It=E2=80=99s not right for their users.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D)</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The stock trades like 10 million shares a day. (T=
here are 207 million shares outstanding.) The record date for the vote was =
June 21. If you owned stock on June 21, you get to vote. If you bought stoc=
k after June 21, you don=E2=80=99t. If you owned stock on June 21 and then =
sold it, you still get to vote. But you are unlikely to care very much. =E2=
=80=9CStockholders as of the close of business on June 21, 2021, the record=
 date for the Special Meeting, should vote their shares even if they no lon=
ger own them,=E2=80=9D said Churchill in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJuZXdzd2lyZS5jb20v=
bmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy9jaHVyY2hpbGwtaXYtcG9sbHMtcmVtYWluLW9wZW4tZm9yLWJ1c2luZXN=
zLWNvbWJpbmF0aW9uLXdpdGgtbHVjaWQtbW90b3JzLTMwMTMzOTQ0My5odG1sP3RjPWVtbF9jbG=
VhcnRpbWU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa1abbe1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> its press release yesterday</a>, but wh=
y should they? It doesn=E2=80=99t affect them anymore. They sold their stoc=
k; if the merger fails, they keep their money, and can have a good laugh at=
 the people who bought the stock from them.=C2=A0</li></ol><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">To the extent SPACs are owned by rapidly day-trading retail sh=
areholders, this is going to be a continuing problem. The good news is that=
 the retail day traders seem to be particularly concentrated in the hottest=
 SPACs, which have the highest prices, so their holders have the most incen=
tive to actually vote. A SPAC that announces a deal and trades to $10.15 is=
 not going to get all that much enthusiasm, but nor is it going to attract =
hordes of Robinhood traders who just forget to vote. Churchill did attract =
those hordes, and they did forget to vote, but eventually it was able to tr=
ack them down and point out that it was in their best interests to vote.</p=
><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cell=
padding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Private markets are the new public markets</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the U.S., the principal=C2=A0<em>le=
gal=C2=A0</em>difference between a =E2=80=9Cpublic=E2=80=9D company and a =
=E2=80=9Cprivate=E2=80=9D company is that you have to be rich to buy shares=
 of a private company, while anyone can buy shares of a public company. Pub=
lic companies=E2=80=99 stocks trade on the stock exchange, and anyone can o=
pen a brokerage account and buy stocks. Private companies=E2=80=99 stocks t=
rade in private transactions, which are subject to more complicated rules, =
but generally speaking if you are an =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGw=
uZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzIzMC41MDE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbf0a6ce8" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">accredited invest=
or</a>=E2=80=9D you are allowed to buy them.[6] The way to qualify as an ac=
credited investor is, traditionally, to have enough money: a net worth (exc=
luding primary residence) of at least $1 million, or income of at least $20=
0,000 per year (or $300,000 for a couple). Recent <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMC0xOTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa6ea1bc0" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">amendments</a=
> to the accredited-investor rules allow you to be accredited by knowledge =
(basically having a securities license) rather than money. And of course ba=
sically any=C2=A0institutional investor will be=C2=A0=E2=80=9Caccredited.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDktMjQvZWFybmluZy10aGUtcmlnaHQtdG8tZ2V=
0LXN3aW5kbGVk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6462c427" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">rough traditional rule</a> is that a=
nyone can buy public stocks, but only institutional investors, hedge funds,=
 dentists, doctors, lawyers, professional athletes, small-business owners =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0honestly it is quite a long list of people who can buy priva=
te stocks? =E2=80=9CAccredited investor=E2=80=9D used to be a pretty exclus=
ive category, but it is much less exclusive today. =E2=80=9CWhen the SEC fi=
rst set its rules of entry for private markets in 1982, <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqL=
mNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9vcHBvcnR1bml0aWVzLXRvLWludmVzdC1pbi1wcml2YXRlLWNvbXBhbmll=
cy1ncm93LTE1Mzc3MjIwMjM_dGVzbGE9eQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf566b158" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">only 1.5 millio=
n households</a> made the cut=E2=80=9D; by 2018, even=C2=A0before the recen=
t amendments to expand the definition,=C2=A0that number was =E2=80=9Cmore t=
han 16 million U.S. households=E2=80=94about one in eight.=E2=80=9D</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this legal difference dramatically understates=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDYtMTkvcHJp=
dmF0ZS1tYXJrZXRzLWNvdWxkLWJlLW1vcmUtcHVibGlj/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf0b4e=
b8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the p=
ractical difference</a> between public and private companies.=C2=A0If you a=
re a prosperous dentist, you are allowed to buy shares in private companies=
, but most private companies won=E2=80=99t sell you any shares. When privat=
e companies want to raise money, they go to big investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0ve=
nture capitalists and private equity funds but also mutual funds and hedge =
funds and strategic investors and SoftBank=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and raise la=
rge chunks of money. And they typically restrict those investors from resel=
ling their stock, so a market doesn=E2=80=99t really develop. And whereas p=
ublic stocks trade on the stock exchange and you can see the price and put =
in an order to buy, private stocks, even when they do trade, usually don=E2=
=80=99t trade on an organized exchange and you can=E2=80=99t just buy them =
through your broker. You have to know the person who=E2=80=99s selling them=
, if you want to buy them. And if you want to sell them, you have to know s=
omeone who=E2=80=99s looking to buy.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One re=
sult of this is that, if you are a prosperous dentist, you can buy the same=
 stock in the same public companies on the same terms as the fanciest hedge=
 fund, but your universe of=C2=A0<em>private=C2=A0</em>investment opportuni=
ties will be totally different from the options available to brand-name ven=
ture capitalists and SoftBank. You will never see any of the deals they see=
, and they will never see any of the deals you see. Probably the deals you =
see will be worse! Because they have lots of money and sophistication, and =
you have just enough money and sophistication to be accredited.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run a company, you might want to be public. The=
re are various advantages to that; the main one is that=C2=A0you can raise =
money from absolutely anyone. Not so long ago, I was <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDUtMDMvc29mdGJhbmstaGFzLWEtYmlnZ2V=
yLXdlaXJkZXItdmlzaW9u/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB400a7f52" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">fond</a> of <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDgtMDUvcHVibGljLW1hcmtldHMtZ=
G9uLXQtbWF0dGVyLWxpa2UtdGhleS11c2VkLXRv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3210db3c" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">downplayin=
g</a> this <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2453701=
