 16px 0;">You could imagine a category like =E2=80=9Cas public as possible =
without actually=C2=A0being public.=E2=80=9D Your stock trades electronical=
ly on a centralized exchange, there are market makers and quoted prices, an=
d anyone who wants to buy it can buy it=C2=A0<em>as long as they are accred=
ited</em>,[7] which is a minority of Americans but now a fairly large minor=
ity. (And an even larger minority of=C2=A0<em>people who buy stocks</em>.) =
If you want to raise money, you can try to sell stock to all the dentists w=
ho trade on the exchange, though realistically the more appealing option is=
 probably to sell stock to big institutions but promise them liquidity in t=
he form of being able to=C2=A0<em>resell=C2=A0</em>their stock to the denti=
sts whenever they want.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The appeal fo=
r companies=C2=A0is the broadest possible access to capital without being p=
ublic: You can sell to venture funds and hedge funds and mutual funds and e=
veryone else who invests privately, but also dentists. The appeal for insti=
