om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Business coaching</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I enjoyed <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013.255073/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlaW5mb3JtYX=
Rpb24uY29tL2FydGljbGVzL3RoZS1jb2FjaC1iZWhpbmQtdGhlLWNvaW5iYXNlLWFuZC1yb2Jpb=
mhvb2QtY2Vvcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbae57f25" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this profile</a> by Kate Clark of Ma=
tt Mochary, a =E2=80=9Cleadership consultant and former startup founder=E2=
=80=9D who coaches founders and chief executive officers:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mochary, 52, guides the founders using tactical =
business lessons gleaned from his career as a founder and private equity in=
vestor, such as how to negotiate compensation with their boards. These he b=
lends with spiritual practices, such as meditation for stress release and =
=E2=80=9Cenergy audits=E2=80=9D to help founders realize what tasks sap the=
m of energy. Those tasks must be delegated, he says.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">By taking his advice, executives can find their =C2=A0=E2=80=9Czo=
ne of genius,=E2=80=9D and learn how to run a company well, he said in a Zo=
om interview from his home in Kauai, Hawaii.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">It is pleasingly specific:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">What he offers is the =E2=80=9CMochary Method,=E2=80=9D which in=
cludes the belief that CEOs should focus only on the tasks that bring them =
energy and that they love. =E2=80=9C[I] teach founders how to create deep r=
elationships, how to create trust,=E2=80=9D Mochary said. ...</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mochary, who wouldn=E2=80=99t go into the specific dis=
cussions he has had with clients, often dives deep into emotional discussio=
ns around fear, anger and shame, say CEOs who have worked with him. He also=
 gives practical suggestions on handling employees and managing meetings, s=
uch as requiring biweekly written feedback between managers and their subor=
dinates. And he has advised founders on how much stock it is appropriate to=
 sell on the secondary market (Mochary recommends selling between $10 milli=
on and $100 million in order to achieve a =E2=80=9Csense of abundance=E2=80=
=9D).</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What do you make of the =
combination of =E2=80=9Cfocus only on the tasks that bring them energy and =
that they love=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9Crequiring biweekly written feedback b=
etween managers and their subordinates=E2=80=9D? Does that mean:</p><ol sty=
le=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Many successful CEOs=C2=A0love giving and re=
ceiving biweekly written feedback, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">CEOs can focus on doing what they love <em>because</em> they can make t=
heir subordinates do stuff they hate?</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>I can kind of see both possibilities? For me personally, nothing brings me=
 less energy than giving or receiving frequent written feedback, but then I=
 have never started a company. Also I am on Twitter all day so revealed pre=
ferences I guess.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also here is an amazing c=
oaching move:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some more extr=
eme cases, Mochary has replaced the CEO entirely for a short period of time=
. In 2017, long before financial software startup Bolt garnered a valuation=
 of $4 billion, Mochary stepped in full time as CEO for over a month. The e=
xperience led to a complete =E2=80=9Cculture reset,=E2=80=9D said co-founde=
r and CEO Ryan Breslow.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The immersive metho=
d helped Breslow, only 23 at the time, learn what qualities are critical to=
 being a good leader, he said. =E2=80=A6 =E2=80=9CIt could take an entire y=
ear for me to tell you what to do as CEO or I could come in and be CEO for =
a few weeks,=E2=80=9D Breslow recalled Mochary saying. =E2=80=9CYou can wat=
ch me and [you=E2=80=99ll] learn 10 times faster.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if he didn=E2=80=99t let the guy come bac=
k? =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s my company now, I=E2=80=99m sorry, this is going t=
o be a valuable learning experience for you at your next startup, bye.=E2=
=80=9D This is a good plot for a business novel.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">The obvious question for services like this is: How do you charge? Th=
ere is a ton of potential leverage here; startups have highly variable outc=
omes, CEO performance is crucial to those outcomes, and making a CEO slight=
ly better=C2=A0can potentially be worth hundreds of millions of dollars. An=
d so traditionally startup founders get coaching from their venture capital=
ists, whose compensation comes in the form of owning shares (that they boug=
ht) in the company: If their advice and mentorship makes a founder better, =
then their shares will be worth a lot more. (Also if they develop a reputat=
ion for making founders better, they will get offered more and better deals=
.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you unbundle coaching from capital, t=
hough, how should the coach charge? The obvious answer would be =E2=80=9Cst=
ock options=E2=80=9D[8] but that seems to be mostly wrong:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Top coaches in the business today charge betwee=
n $5,000 and $10,000 per month, according to people familiar with the indus=
try. Mochary charges $12,500 a month for sessions, which he holds on Zoom o=
n a monthly basis, if not more often.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Until=
 this year, Mochary would counsel executives at no charge, a choice he said=
 he could make because the 2005 sale of his startup Totality had made him w=
ealthy. The pro bono move bothered some other coaches, according to one who=
 asked not to be named. Mochary would sometimes ask executives to instead d=
onate equity to his foundation, or he would invest in their startup.</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHe would invest in their st=
artup=E2=80=9D seems reasonable. =E2=80=9CA flat monthly fee=E2=80=9D is, y=
ou know, fine, but one worries about the alignment of incentives. =E2=80=9C=
Free, I just love startups=E2=80=9D is sort of the deep Silicon Valley answ=
er: You do stuff to make the startup ecosystem better, which raises your st=
atus in that ecosystem, which will eventually turn out to make you rich eve=
n if the causal mechanism is initially unclear.[9] (It helps to be rich to =
begin with.)</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspa=
cing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
