</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say that you like the st=
ock of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. and you want to buy, say, $1,000 wor=
th of it. Let=E2=80=99s say you don=E2=80=99t have $1,000. How can you buy =
the stock anyway? A classic answer is =E2=80=9Ca margin loan=E2=80=9D: You =
go to your broker, put in $500, your broker lends you $500, and you buy $1,=
000 worth of stock. When you sell it, you have to pay your broker back, and=
 you have to pay interest, but if it goes up you get basically all of the u=
pside.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if you don=E2=80=99t have $500?=
 You might look into options. A call option to buy 100 shares of AMC stock =
(about $3,600 worth) for $60 a share next month currently goes for about $2=
00.[10] If you buy that and AMC doubles to $72 next month, you will make $1=
,000.[11] That=E2=80=99s roughly what you would have made buying $1,000 wor=
th of stock. Of course if it goes up less you=E2=80=99ll make less; if it g=
oes up 50% you=E2=80=99ll make nothing and lose your $200. This is not a pe=
rfect substitute for buying the stock. But it=E2=80=99s something. It=E2=80=
=99s a leveraged bet on the stock, a way to spend a relatively small amount=
 of money to bet on a huge rally in AMC stock.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">What if you don=E2=80=99t have $200? What if you have, say, zero dollar=
s? Will anyone provide you with leverage where you put up nothing, they put=
 up the money, you buy the AMC stock, if it goes up you collect the profits=
, and you never pay them back? When you put it like that the answer is no, =
obviously not, but it=E2=80=99s worth a try?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24537013=
